The fact that the course of thought is rambling is the key to an understanding of the Epistle. F or this arrangement is not the result of carelessness3 Horace followed this unsystematic and yet closely knit succession of topios from deliberate choice. He was not trying to compose a treatise, but to write an epistula, a semo. Like any epistle, it is addressed to certain persons, and, like any serum, it follows the line of easy transitiou by suggestion from one topic to another. This is in itself a form of art, the particular form to which Horace had trained himself, and this Epistle is to be interpreted precisely as Epist. 2, 1 and 2, 2 are to be interpreted.
